Boil a full kettle.

Pour the boiled water into a #large saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} on high
heat. Add the @Basmati rice{150%g} and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Cover with a
#lid{} and leave to the side until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into
thin strips.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the
@diced British chicken breast{260%g}, @diced chorizo{90%g} and sliced pepper.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Stir-fry until the chicken is browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its
> packaging.

Add the garlic, @Mexican style spice mix{1%tsp} (add less if you'd prefer things
milder) and @tomato puree{30%g} to the chicken. Stir-fry for ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the @chicken stock paste{10%g}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{150%ml} for the
sauce (see pantry for both amounts). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Bring the chicken to the boil, then lower the heat.

Simmer, stirring occasionally, until the sauce has thickened and the chicken is
cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, cut the @medium tomato{1} into 1cm pieces.

Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Pop the tomatoes and half the coriander into a #bowl{} with a drizzle of @oil{}.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then set your salsa aside.

When everything's ready, fluff the rice up with a #fork{}. Stir through the
remaining coriander, then share between your bowls.

Taste the chicken fajita mix, season with more @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed,
then spoon it over the rice.

Top with the salsa and a big dollop of @soured cream{75%g}.

Enjoy!